'''Bruno P. Maddox''' (born 1969) is a British [[literary fiction|literary novelist]] and journalist who is best known for his critically lauded novel ''My Little Blue Dress'' (2001) and for his satirical magazine essays.

After graduating from [[Harvard University]] in 1992, Maddox began his career reviewing books for ''[[The New York Times Book Review]]'' and ''[[The Washington Post]] Book World''.  In early 1996, he was appointed to an editorship at ''[[Spy (magazine)|Spy]]'' magazine and within a few months he was promoted to editor-in-chief, a position he held until the magazine shut down in 1998.  Maddox wrote ''My Little Blue Dress'' between 1999 and 2001.  Since its publication, he has focused on writing satirical essays for magazines such as ''[[Gear (magazine)|GEAR]]'' and ''[[Travel + Leisure]]''; he also contributes a monthly humor column to ''[[Discover (magazine)|Discover]]'' magazine called &quot;Blinded by Science&quot;, drawing on his early exposure to science and technology.  Maddox is likewise a [[contributing editor]] to the American edition of ''[[The Week]]'' magazine.&lt;ref name=TheWeekGreenIssue/&gt;

==Early years==
Maddox was born in London in 1969 to former ''[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]'' editor Sir [[John Maddox]], a writer on science and nature, and [[Brenda Maddox]], a biographer of [[Rosalind Franklin]], [[W.B. Yeats]], [[Nora Barnacle]] and several others.&lt;ref name=NinaBlount/&gt;&lt;ref name=AboutBBS&gt;{{cite web|title=About Blinded By Science columns|work=[[Discover Magazine|Discover]]|url=http://discovermagazine.com/columns/blinded-by-science|accessdate=25 July 2007}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal|title=Touching base|journal=[[Nature (journal)|Nature Genetics]]|volume=28|year=2001|pages=305|url=http://www.nature.com/ng/journal/v28/n4/full/ng0801_305.html|doi=10.1038/91050|accessdate=25 July 2007|issue=4}}&lt;/ref&gt; He has one sister, [[Bronwen Maddox|Bronwen]], who became a journalist and is Chief Foreign Commentator of ''[[The Times]]'' as of 2008.&lt;ref name=PenguinBio&gt;{{cite web|title=About Bruno Maddox|publisher=[[Penguin Group (USA)]]|url=http://us.penguingroup.com/nf/Author/AuthorPage/0,,1000037427,00.html|accessdate=25 July 2007}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=About Bronwen Maddox|work=The Times |location=London |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/columnists/bronwen_maddox/|accessdate=21 January 2008  | first=Philippe | last=Naughton}}&lt;/ref&gt; Maddox enjoyed a privileged life during his childhood and youth, because of his father's position as editor of ''Nature'', encountering some of the leading scientific thinkers of the day and enjoying dinners with figures such as [[James D. Watson|James Watson]] and [[Sir Fred Hoyle]].&lt;ref name=AboutBBS/&gt;

Despite his family's background in science, Maddox was interested in the [[humanities]] while he attended [[Westminster School]], an independent boys' school in London. Maddox went on to study [[English literature]] at [[Harvard University]] and graduated in 1992.&lt;ref name=PublicityMaterial/&gt;  He published his first and only article in the [[student newspaper]] ''[[The Harvard Crimson]]'' during his [[Student#Post-second year|senior]] year.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|author=Bruno Maddox|title=Cabot Turns Trash Into Art: Superintendent Urges Residents on to Ecolympic Laurels|date=15 February 1991|work=[[The Harvard Crimson]]|url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article.aspx?ref=243329|accessdate=25 July 2007}}&lt;/ref&gt; He won the undergraduate [[Thomas T. Hoopes, Class of 1919, Prize|Thomas Temple Hoopes Prize]] for his senior thesis &quot;on the use of adjectives in restaurant menus&quot; titled ''Maltese: A Gastrosophic Theory of Reading''.&lt;ref name=PenguinBio/&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book|title=Maltese: A Gastrosophic Theory of Reading|author=Bruno Maddox|year=1992|publisher=Thesis (A.B., Honors in English and American Literature and Language)--Harvard University, 1992|pages=120 pages|url=http://books.google.com/?id=pc7BIQAACAAJ}}&lt;/ref&gt; After graduation Maddox moved from [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]] to Moscow—where he worked for three weeks as the English-language editor of a Russian magazine—and then to New York City, where he spent two years working odd jobs, including hand-delivering celebrity invitations to local parties.&lt;ref name=ACE_interview/&gt;

Maddox's freelance writing career began in 1994, when he became a book reviewer for ''[[The New York Times Book Review]]'' and ''[[The Washington Post]]'', where he developed a reputation for writing scathing reviews that would later help him land a job as an editor at ''[[Spy (magazine)|Spy]]'' magazine.&lt;ref name=Andelman_interview/&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=One Last Hurrah|author=Bruno Maddox|date=23 January 1994|work=[[The Washington Post]] through ''[http://www.lexisnexis.com/universe LexisNexis Academic]''}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=In Short: Nonfiction|author=Bruno Maddox|date=17 July 1994|work=The New York Times}}&lt;/ref&gt; Maddox described his book reviewing style as &quot;pretty vicious&quot;, and quipped that he &quot;was a frustrated, twenty-something guy, sitting in his bedroom venting existential rage on these nasty academics&quot;.&lt;ref name=Andelman_interview/&gt; His last book review for ''The Washington Post'' was in late 1996; however, he continued reviewing for ''The New York Times'' up until 1998, contributing only a couple of reviews thereafter.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=Monsters of Our Own Making|author=Bruno Maddox|date=29 September 1996|work=[[The Washington Post]] through ''[http://www.lexisnexis.com/universe LexisNexis Academic]''}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=Blade Runner|author=Bruno Maddox|date=22 March 1998|work=The New York Times|url=http://www.nytimes.com/books/98/03/22/reviews/980322.22maddoxt.html|accessdate=1 September 2007}}&lt;/ref&gt;

At the beginning of the [[dot-com boom]], Maddox found full-time work at an information technology company, where he worked for a year and a half.&lt;ref name=ACE_interview/&gt;

==Editorship of ''Spy'' magazine==
In mid-1996, Maddox was hired as a [[senior editor]] at ''[[Spy (magazine)|Spy]]'' magazine, a [[satirical]] monthly, in New York City.&lt;ref name=Andelman_interview/&gt;  ''Spy'' had ceased publication in 1994 but was quickly resuscitated under new ownership by Sussex Publishers Inc., which reduced the magazine's frequency from ten to six issues a year.&lt;ref name=Sussex&gt;{{cite news|title=Spy goes under for the last time|author=Neil Cassidy|date=1 March 1998|publisher=''Folio: The Magazine for Magazine Management'' reprinted by FindArticles.com|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m3065/is_n3_v27/ai_20350760|accessdate=15 April 2007}}&lt;/ref&gt;  At ''Spy'', Maddox was assisted by deputy editor Adam Lehner, a satirist.&lt;ref name=Salon-Spy&gt;{{cite news|title=Media Circus: Spy vs. Spy|author=[[James Surowiecki]]|date=2 September 1997|publisher=[[Salon.com]]|url=http://www.salon.com/sept97/media/media970902.html|accessdate=25 July 2007|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20070615043026/http://www.salon.com/sept97/media/media970902.html &lt;!--Added by H3llBot--&gt;|archivedate=15 June 2007}}&lt;/ref&gt; In December 1996, Maddox was promoted to editor-in-chief;&lt;ref name=Andelman_interview&gt;{{cite news|title=Mr. Media Spies on Spy!|author=Bob Andelman|date=14 April 1997|work=[[Universal Press Syndicate]]|url=http://www.andelman.com/mrmedia/97/04.14.97.html |accessdate=25 July 2007 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20001101213832/http://www.andelman.com/mrmedia/97/04.14.97.html |archivedate = 1 November 2000}}&lt;/ref&gt; his editorial team included [[Jared Paul Stern]] and, beginning in late 1997, future screenwriter [[William Monahan]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=Reporter Was Quick Study in Art of Mingling With the Rich and Glamorous|author=Marc Santora|date=9 April 2006|work=The New York Times|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2006/04/09/nyregion/09stern.html|accessdate=8 August 2007 }}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=Standing at the corner of Shakespeare and Scorsese|author=Sam Allis|date=3 October 2006|work=The Boston Globe|url=http://www.boston.com/ae/movies/articles/2006/10/03/standing_at_the_corner_of_shakespeare_and_scorcese/|accessdate=8 August 2007 }}&lt;/ref&gt;

Maddox wanted to turn ''Spy'' into a national magazine rather than build on its legacy of covering stories that centered on New York.  According to Maddox, two factors motivated the shift of [[target market]]. The magazine's past objects of satire, the &quot;cheesy villains who anointed themselves as targets&quot; in the 1980s, were no longer on the national stage. Meanwhile, the &quot;sins of the '90s [were] those of a private, quiet cultivation of a sense of purity&quot;, and were harder to expose or ridicule.&lt;ref name=Salon-Spy/&gt;

In early 1998, Sussex Publishers increased ''Spy''&lt;nowiki&gt;'&lt;/nowiki&gt;s frequency from six to nine issues a year in an effort to boost readership and ad pages. ''Spy'''s paid circulation continued to drop during Maddox's tenure, and in March 1998, the magazine once again ceased publication.  Sussex's President and CEO John Colman concluded that &quot;[despite the] great work by Bruno and his team, there just wasn't the [advertiser and consumer] acceptance that we need to make it financially viable&quot;.&lt;ref name=Sussex/&gt;  Maddox conceded that &quot;a satirical magazine in New York in the late Nineties really had no function&quot;, because &quot;everyone was being very modest and coy&quot;.&lt;ref name=NinaBlount&gt;{{cite news|title=my little blue dress: bruno maddox talks to ivenus about the post-post-postmodern novel|author=Nina Blount|year=2001|publisher=iVenus.com|url=http://www.ivenus.com/culture/books/features/CU-FP-FullLength-wk58.asp|accessdate=1 August 2007| archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20050524233446/http://www.ivenus.com/culture/books/features/CU-FP-FullLength-wk58.asp| archivedate = 24 May 2005}}&lt;/ref&gt;

==''My Little Blue Dress''==
