In 1999, Maddox sold the advance rights to his first novel, ''My Little Blue Dress'', to a German publisher based on a five-page fax proposal he sent on the advice of his [[literary agent]] [[John Brockman (literary agent)|John Brockman]].&lt;ref name=ACE_interview&gt;{{cite web|title=Back in the (Day) Job – Bruno Maddox|author=Cristín Leach|date=10 May 2001|work=[[Raidió Teilifís Éireann|Radio Telefís Éireann]]|url=http://www.rte.ie/arts/2001/0510/dayjob.html|accessdate=25 July 2007}}&lt;/ref&gt;  Within a week Brockman managed to sell the rights to the novel to publishers in an additional eight countries on the strength of the proposal alone.&lt;ref name=prov&gt;{{cite news|title=Agent Provocateur|author=Warren St. John|date=September 1999|work=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] magazine|url=http://www.wired.com/wired/archive/7.09/brockman.html|accessdate=8 August 2007}}&lt;/ref&gt; (Maddox had not yet written even an initial [[manuscript]].)

{{cquote|It was a pretty terrifying experience, suddenly having a legal obligation to write an extremely difficult post-modern novel having never written anything before and also, stupidly, I told him I could do it in six months, which was just a conversational thing until it turned up in black and white in my contract. The six months came and went and my reputation in publishing at the moment is a reflection of the two and a half years I spent writing it longer than I should have done. The Dutch cancelled when the Millennium came and went, they decided it was a millennial book, but weirdly they would have accepted it in November of 1999, for a few days of millennial reading, they failed to see that it is obviously a twenty-first century book.|||Bruno Maddox, on the publishing of his first novel.&lt;ref name=ACE_interview/&gt;}}

''My Little Blue Dress'' was published in 2001 by [[Viking Press]], a [[Penguin Group]] [[imprint]]. The novel begins as a [[memoir]] of a hundred-year-old woman, but several chapters later reveals itself to be a spoof of the genre. The protagonist is a fictional Bruno Maddox who is desperately attempting to create a forgery of an old woman's memoir in a single night.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news| title=Books: A better shot at the Bloke's First Book|author=Brandon Robshaw|work=[[The Independent]] reprinted by FindArticles.com|date=2 June 2001|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4158/is_20010602/ai_n14385504|accessdate=14 August 2007| archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080202081236/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4158/is_20010602/ai_n14385504| archivedate = 2 February 2008}}&lt;/ref&gt; Several book reviewers avoided spoiling the novel's satire but others gave away its premise, reasoning that the publisher &quot;reveal[s] all on the book jacket anyway&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=My Little Blue Dress by Bruno Maddox: Viking, U.S., 2001|author=Michael Garry Smout|date=January–February 2002|work=The Barcelona Review|url=http://www.barcelonareview.com/rev/28.htm|accessdate=8 August 2007 }}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=Salon-Bluedress&gt;{{cite news|title=&quot;My Little Blue Dress&quot; by Bruno Maddox|author=Maria Russo|date=17 May 2001|publisher=[[Salon.com]]|url=http://archive.salon.com/books/review/2001/05/21/maddox/|accessdate=15 August 2007}}&lt;/ref&gt; The novel's intrigue lies in the mysterious reason compelling the fictional Maddox to forge a memoir.&lt;ref name=Salon-Bluedress/&gt;

Critics applauded ''My Little Blue Dress'' but also expressed some reservations. For example, [[Salon.com]]'s Maria Russo cautioned that the novel &quot;is one of those 'don't try this at home' literary experiments that could easily have turned into an unreadable, pretentious disaster&quot;, but concluded that Maddox &quot;pulls it off with a kind of fearless pizzazz&quot;.&lt;ref name=Salon-Bluedress/&gt;  ''The New York Times''' [[Emily Barton]] conceded that &quot;for all its blunders&quot;, Maddox delivers &quot;a winsome and vastly entertaining novel&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=Enough About Me|author=Emily Barton|date=27 May 2001|work=The New York Times|url=http://www.nytimes.com/books/01/05/27/reviews/010527.27bartont.html|accessdate=15 August 2007}}&lt;/ref&gt;

In an interview, Maddox praised [[Bret Easton Ellis]]’s 1991 novel ''[[American Psycho]]'', stating that he drew inspiration from protagonist [[Patrick Bateman]]'s long-winded monologues about [[Phil Collins]], restaurants, clothes, and how to remove blood from his carpets.&lt;ref name=NinaBlount/&gt;

In 2001, Maddox promoted his first novel on a joint book tour billed as the &quot;Minor Novelists Tour&quot; with his friend [[William Monahan]], another former ''Spy'' editor, but it was interrupted by the 9/11 attacks. Monahan's ''[[Light House: A Trifle]]'' was also published by a Penguin imprint.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=Writer's 'trifle' Aims Higher|author=Darcy Cosper|date=2 October 2001|work=[[The Hartford Courant]] through ''[http://www.lexisnexis.com/universe LexisNexis Academic]''}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=Authors at Real Art Ways|date=20 September 2001|work=[[The Hartford Courant]] through ''[http://www.lexisnexis.com/universe LexisNexis Academic]''}}&lt;/ref&gt; Several years later, Maddox gave some indication that he was working on a [[film adaptation]] of ''My Little Blue Dress'',&lt;ref name=NYPost1&gt;A note at the end of several of Maddox's book reviews read, &quot;Bruno Maddox is adapting his novel 'My Little Blue Dress' for the screen.&quot; See Maddox's [http://cache.zoominfo.com/CachedPage/?archive_id=0&amp;page_id=710684732&amp;page_url=%2f%2fwww.nypost.com%2fentertainment%2f25175.htm&amp;page_last_updated=6%2f6%2f2004+9%3a22%3a28+AM&amp;firstName=Bruno&amp;lastName=Maddox review] of [[P. J. O'Rourke]]'s ''Peace Kills: America's Fun New Imperialism'' (''New York Post'', 6 June 2004) and his [http://cache.zoominfo.com/CachedPage/?archive_id=0&amp;page_id=733686384&amp;page_url=%2f%2fwww.nypost.com%2fentertainment%2f26359.htm&amp;page_last_updated=6%2f27%2f2004+9%3a19%3a59+AM&amp;firstName=Bruno&amp;lastName=Maddox review] of George Hagen's ''The Laments'' (''New York Post'', 27 June 2004). &lt;!--These articles formerly linked to Maddox's ZoomInfo profile at http://www.zoominfo.com/people/Maddox_Bruno_521736090.aspx. --&gt;&lt;/ref&gt; but it is unknown whether Maddox completed the script.&lt;ref&gt;As of 2007 there is no further evidence that Maddox completed the script.&lt;/ref&gt;

==Recent essays==
After the publication of ''My Little Blue Dress'' in 2001, Maddox was reportedly working on a second novel set in California, where &quot;everyone's aspirational and deluded&quot; and the &quot;people are quite happy being waiters and dreaming of stardom&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=All About Me|author=Tom Dart|date=2 June 2001|work=[[The Times]] through ''[http://www.lexisnexis.com/universe LexisNexis Academic]''}}&lt;/ref&gt; As of 2009, however, no manuscript has been forthcoming.&lt;ref&gt;As of 2009 a second novel from Maddox has not been published, however, in a story (dated 16 Oct 2009) by Bruno Maddox it is written that [http://significantobjects.com/2009/10/16/thai-hooks/ &quot;Bruno Maddox is at work on his second novel.&quot;]&lt;/ref&gt;

{{Rquote|right|I don't like to think in terms of careers, I want to move from project to project&amp;nbsp;… I think like anything, it's good to keep changing. I just want to live with integrity.|Bruno Maddox, on his lack of a career path.&lt;ref name=ACE_interview/&gt;}}

Since 2001, Maddox has written numerous articles for popular magazines, such as the now-defunct ''[[Gear (magazine)|GEAR]]''.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=DiscoBlog: Before it was Real (9/11)|author=Susan Kruglinski|date=11 September 2006|work=[[Discover Magazine|Discover]]|url=http://discovermagazine.com/blogs/discoblog/archive/2006/09/12/before-it-was-real-9-11|accessdate=12 August 2007}} {{Dead link|date=April 2012|bot=H3llBot}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=Bob G. Jr. on what did in Gear|author=Jeff Bercovici|date=8 April 2003|work=Media Life magazine|url=http://www.medialifemagazine.com/news2003/apr03/apr07/2_tues/news3tuesday.html|accessdate=14 August 2007}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=Gabbing With The Gooch|author=Jeff Bercovici|date=1 April 2004|publisher=''Folio: The Magazine for Magazine Management'' reprinted by FindArticles.com|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m3065/is_4_33/ai_n6077579|accessdate=14 August 2007}}&lt;/ref&gt;  Published one year after the [[11 September 2001 attacks]], his essay &quot;Before It Was Real&quot; describes the callousness of the terrorists who flew into the [[World Trade Center]] through the experience of playing a [[flight simulator]] game.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=Before It Was Real|author=Bruno Maddox|date=September 2002|work=[[Gear (magazine)|GEAR]] magazine}}&lt;/ref&gt;  Another example of Maddox's work is his 2003 profile of [[Karl Wenclas]], leader of the [[Underground Literary Alliance]], titled &quot;The Angriest Book Club in America&quot; and published in the fashion magazine ''[[BlackBook Magazine|BlackBook]]''.&lt;ref name=Gawker&gt;{{cite news|title=Diary: The ULA profiled|date=1 August 2003|publisher=[[Gawker.com]]|url=http://gawker.com/news/diary/the-ula-profiled-12921.php|accessdate=14 August 2007}}&lt;/ref&gt;  Wenclas later derided Maddox for distorting the Underground Literary Alliance in his ''BlackBook'' essay and summed up the article as &quot;riddled with falsehoods&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=Distorting the Message|author=[[Karl Wenclas]]|date=6 October 2006|publisher=AttackingtheDemi-Puppets (Wenclas' blog)|url=http://kingwenclas.blogspot.com/2006_10_01_archive.html|accessdate=14 August 2007}}&lt;/ref&gt;

In late 2003, Maddox began to contribute articles regularly to ''[[Travel + Leisure]]''. His first article in the magazine was called &quot;The Concorde, R.I.P.&quot;, which chronicled his flight aboard the supersonic [[Concorde]] airplane before it was decommissioned; it was later included in ''The Best Travel Writing 2005'', the second volume of the annual Travelers’ Tales series.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=The Concorde, R.I.P.|author=Bruno Maddox|date=October 2003|work=[[Travel + Leisure]]|url=http://www.travelandleisure.com/articles/the-concorde-rip|accessdate=13 April 2007}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book|title=The Best Travel Writing 2005: True Stories from Around the World|editor=O'Reilly, James, Larry Habegger, and Sean O'Reilly|chapter=The Concorde, R.I.P.|author=Bruno Maddox|location=San Francisco, Calif|publisher=Travelers' Tales|year=2005|isbn=978-1-932361-16-2}}&lt;/ref&gt; In 2004 Maddox began working as a [[contributing editor]] for the American edition of ''[[The Week]]'' magazine and as of 2007 continues to contribute weekly to the print issue, handling sections including &quot;Main Stories&quot;, &quot;Talking Points&quot;, and &quot;Only in America&quot;.&lt;ref name=TheWeekGreenIssue&gt;{{cite news|title=Green Issue's Masthead|date=23 April 2007|work=[[The Week]]|url=http://green.theweekmagazine.com/mainstories.html |accessdate=23 April 2007 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20070423041446/http://green.theweekmagazine.com/mainstories.html |archivedate = 23 April 2007}}&lt;/ref&gt; He also reviewed several books for ''[[The New York Post]]'' in 2004 and 2005.&lt;ref name=NYPost1/&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=With Friends Like These...|author=Bruno Maddox|date=13 February 2005|work=The New York Post|url=http://mikealbo.com/PDFS/nypost_entertainment.pdf|format = PDF| accessdate=27 August 2007}}&lt;/ref&gt;

In 2006, Maddox began contributing a regular humor column called &quot;Blinded by Science&quot; to ''[[Discover Magazine|Discover]]'' magazine. His writing draws upon his childhood exposure to science; due to his father's career, his family was immersed in science and he was regularly exposed to scientists at social events.&lt;ref name=AboutBBS/&gt; Maddox's first year's columns earned him a nod as a finalist in the 2007 [[National Magazine Award]]s' &quot;Columns and Commentary&quot; category.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=New York is tops in magazine awards: Takes home five Ellies, the most of any magazine|author=Diego Vasquez|date=2 May 2007|work=Media Life magazine|url=http://www.medialifemagazine.com/artman2/publish/Magazines_22/New_York_is_tops_in_magazine_awards_11827.asp|accessdate=25 July 2007}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Maddox's ''Discover'' columns are occasionally criticized; his essay &quot;Fictional Reality&quot;, in particular, has been controversial. Maddox declared science fiction obsolete in his essay &quot;Fictional Reality&quot; and was roundly criticized in the [[blogosphere]], most notably by ''[[Scientific American]]''&lt;nowiki&gt;'&lt;/nowiki&gt;s J.R. Minkel. Maddox wrote that &quot;fiction—all fiction—finally became obsolete as a delivery system for big ideas&quot; as a result of the &quot;scarcity of foreseeable future&quot;, citing the decline of author [[Michael Crichton]]'s work as evidence.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=Blinded by Science: Fictional Reality|author=Maddox, Bruno|date=20 July 2007|work=Discover|url=http://discovermagazine.com/2007/aug/blinded-by-science }}&lt;/ref&gt; Minkel lambasted Maddox and pointed to author [[Neal Stephenson]]'s cutting-edge work as proof to the contrary, venturing that &quot;science fiction writers can ''dictate'' the future if they have the vim and vision&quot;.
&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=Science fiction is not obsolete—do you read me Bruno Maddox?|author=J.R. Minkel|date=8 August 2007|work=[[Scientific American]]|url=http://blog.sciam.com/index.php?title=science_fiction_is_not_dead_do_you_read|accessdate=8 August 2007| archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20071020114650/http://blog.sciam.com/index.php?title=science_fiction_is_not_dead_do_you_read| archivedate = 20 October 2007}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=DiscoBlog: Sci-Fi Died... But It Came Back in a Different Form!|author=Amos Kenigsberg|date=9 August 2007|work=Discover|url=http://discovermagazine.com/blogs/discoblog/archive/2007/08/10/sci-fi-died-but-it-came-back-in-a-different-form|accessdate=12 August 2007}}&lt;/ref&gt;

One of Maddox's most recent ''Discover'' essays, &quot;The James Watson Affair&quot;, examines comments made by [[James Watson]] in an article in London's ''[[The Times|Sunday Times]]'' which led to Watson's suspension at the laboratory where he worked and his eventual retirement, and is skeptical of critics who found Watson's comment about black employees &quot;not that big a deal&quot; yet charged him with racism for his proposition on black African intelligence; in conclusion, Maddox derides the views held by several critics, stating that in comparison to Watson's statements, &quot;the most ignorant and hurtful idea of all, of course, is that the entire topic of race and genes and intelligence is off-limits to all right-thinking, compassionate people, just on principle&quot;, which pejoratively assumes &quot;that some races ''are'' innately and immutably much less intelligent than others&quot;. Maddox's essay, although published in the March 2008 printed edition of ''Discover'', has not been published online.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |title=The elementary DNA of Dr Watson |author=Charlotte Hunt-Grubbe |date=14 October 2007 |work=The Times |location=London |url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/books/article2630748.ece  }}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|title=Blinded by Science: The James Watson affair has this writer wondering: Who are the real racists out there?|author=Bruno Maddox |date=March 2008|work=Discover|url=}}&lt;/ref&gt;

==Style==
Satire is evident in much of Maddox's work, from his years as editor-in-chief for ''[[Spy (magazine)|Spy]]'' magazine to his numerous articles in ''[[Travel + Leisure]]'', and his novel ''My Little Blue Dress''. Maddox's satirical tendencies extend to his interviews and publicity materials. In one interview he made the preposterous claim that he once &quot;spent 2 days being a personal assistant to a mafia boss in New York&quot;.&lt;ref name=ACE_interview/&gt;  Maddox's [[Penguin Group|Penguin]] biography skewers his own career, claiming he &quot;elevated [''Spy''] to within spitting distance of its former glory, then accidentally bankrupted it after two short years&quot;, which led ''[[The Harvard Crimson]]'', his alma mater's student newspaper, to speculate that &quot;Maddox himself had a hand in writing&quot; it.&lt;ref name=PublicityMaterial&gt;{{cite news|title=Reading. Period|author=P. Patty Li|date=4 May 2001|work=[[The Harvard Crimson]]|url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article.aspx?ref=104286|accessdate=25 July 2007}}&lt;/ref&gt; Maddox's [[popular science]] columns for ''[[Discover (magazine)|Discover]]'' magazine impart his own personal views on science with a markedly humorous and [[skeptical]] bent.&lt;ref name=AboutBBS/&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|title=Math Digest: Summaries of Media Coverage of Math|author=Lisa DeKeukelaere|month=June | year=2007|work=[[American Mathematical Society]]|url=http://www.ams.org/mathmedia/mathdigest/md-200706-toc.html|accessdate=14 August 2007}}&lt;/ref&gt;

